Prompt: One of the typical tasks of a historian of science is to bring together ideas across time and space. For this prompt, you are going to pick a concept, idea, phrase, or method from two different weeks and analyze it/them. You can pick the same idea in two different weeks (comparing across contexts) or you can pick different ideas from different weeks that you think are in conversation with each other. Though you can pick something from a secondary source or lecture, it is typically easier to approach this assignment using the primary sources, and relying on the secondary sources and lecture for context and detail. The goal is to analyze (not summarize) the concept(s) or idea(s) by comparison across time and space. The paper might ask, for example: How do different ideas receive the same label? Why does the “same” problem change over time? Or is a particular idea interestingly context-invariant? Are two different concepts actually quite similar, but labeled differently? What does the juxtaposition tell us about the history of science over time? You do not need to do additional research, but should use any relevant material from the readings and lectures, except that you cannot use the same primary source you used in your first paper. You should choose evidence carefully and think broadly: if you don’t use course material that would have improved your argument, that can be held against you. All written material used should be clearly cited in footnotes, giving the author, short title, and page number (if appropriate); if you use material from lectures or discussions, you can cite the relevant date. At the top of the paper, you should give the essay a title and provide your name (of course). The analysis itself should be between 1500 and 2000 words total (not including notes). Please use double spacing, 1” margins and page numbers.
